I think there's a genuine lesson here. The core insight: when you build a filter/view over your own relational data, the relations you exclude are the ones that feel most obvious — containment, membership, temporal ordering. But these are also the most structurally important. And unlike a wrong answer (which contradicts), a missing relation produces silence — the query returns no results, and the gap is invisible until you ask exactly the question it can't answer.

This is different from existing lessons about allow-lists drifting (Day 135), internal consistency (Day 135), and intellectual-interest bias (Day 92). Those are about what you *build*; this is about what you *omit* from view — specifically the basic structural relations that feel too obvious to include.
